node.text: Have you been eating sushi wrong? 🍣 We spoke to a Michelin star chef in Tokyo to learn the proper technique. Koji Sawada says when you're eating nigiri, you should dip the fish in the soy sauce, not the rice, and the fish should touch your tongue first. node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNN on September 18, 2021. May be an image of 3 people, child, people standing and text that says 'This single mom is is braiding kids' hair for free to to help other struggling parents CNN'.

node.text:
Brittany Starks knows what it's like to struggle. Despite being a single mother who lives paycheck to paycheck and has been homeless twice, Starks hasn't allowed her hardships to break her spirit. She posted on Facebook that she'll braid kid's hair for free, so they can go back to school feeling happy and confident. She was flooded with requests and has already braided the hair of more than 35 children. Each appointment takes between four to six hours.⁠
⁠
"I wanted to do something for the parents like me whose money is going to feeding their children and making sure they have a roof over their head," Starks told CNN. "I wasn't expecting a big reaction. I thought I'd maybe get five kids or so, but I didn't realize how huge the need was for this."⁠
⁠
(📸: Raven Starks)

node.text: This is the heartbreaking and shocking scene at the US-Mexico border right now. @rosaflorescnn took an aerial tour of the region and saw thousands of migrants waiting to be processed by US immigrant authorities.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNN on September 17, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Uncontrollable vomiting due to marijuana use is on the rise, a new study finds. The research on this bizarre condition is still spotty. CNN'.

node.text:
Habitual users of cannabis, including teens, are showing up in emergency rooms complaining of severe intestinal distress. “They vomit and then just continue to vomit whatever they have in their stomach, which can go on for hours,” said Dr. Sam Wang, a pediatric emergency medicine specialist and toxicologist at Children’s Hospital Colorado. “They often say they took a scalding hot shower before they came to the ER but it didn’t help.” This bizarre condition is called cannabis hyperemesis syndrome, or CHS.⁠
